<subSubSection id="C3186552FFDDE356FF235230FCB0FC3B" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BBD36D9FFDDE356FF235230FD65FDC6" blockId="19.[151,1437,1386,2025]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis id="B976EACBFFDDE356FF235230FEBBFE8B" bold="true" box="[199,347,1386,1412]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Description:</emphasis>
<emphasis id="B976EACBFFDDE356FE865230FE56FE8B" box="[354,438,1386,1412]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Female</emphasis>
(MACN-Ar 33021): Carapace length 1.48, width 1.18, narrowed in eye region. Carapace covered with low tubercles. Palpal tarsus length 0.33. Sternum length 0.92, width 0.90. Length of tibia/metatarsus: I, 1.10/0.83; II, 0.87/0.70; III, 0.67/0.63; IV, 1.17/1.17. Spines: Leg I, femur p 1ap. Leg cuspules absent. Distal segments of leg I and II with strong scopulae, metatarsi of legs III and IV with distinct preening comb. Opisthosoma length 2.60. Color in ethanol: Prosoma brownish-orange, lighter distally. Chelicerae brownish-orange. Legs yellowish-orange, tibiae and patellae of leg I darker. Sternum brownish-orange, lighter distally. Opisthosoma grayishbrown, with chevrons. Venter grayish, with pair of longitudinal dark stripes. Epigyne (
<figureCitation id="13392A5CFFDDE356FBB15118FB44FD52" box="[1109,1188,1602,1629]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="23.[151,250,1436,1460]" captionTargetBox="[173,1413,273,1413]" captionTargetId="figure-55@23.[173,1413,273,1413]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 15. Meriola balcarce, genitalia. a, Female epigyne, ventral view (MACN-Ar 33021); b, vulva, cleared, dorsal view. c, male, left palp, prolateral view (MACN-Ar 33021); d, same, ventral view; e, same, retrolateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4559199" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4559199/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
a–b): single plate with wide anterior hood. Copulatory openings in posterior position; copulatory ducts very short, S2 elongated, widened anteriorly, receptacle of copulatory ducts small and rounded, posterior to primary spermathecae. Primary spermathecae small and oval, half the size of CDR.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBD36D9FFDDE356FF235188FD5FFDE2" blockId="19.[151,1437,1386,2025]" box="[199,703,1746,1773]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis id="B976EACBFFDDE356FF235188FEE1FDE3" box="[199,257,1746,1772]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Male</emphasis>
described by 
<bibRefCitation id="EF934B28FFDDE356FE795188FD5BFDE2" author="Platnick, N. I. &amp; Ewing, C." box="[413,699,1746,1773]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" pagination="1 - 41" refId="ref46490" refString="Platnick, N. I. &amp; Ewing, C. (1995) A revision of the tracheline spiders (Araneae, Corinnidae) of southern South America. American Museum Novitates, 3128, 1 - 41." type="journal article" year="1995">Platnick &amp; Ewing (1995)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBD36D9FFDDE356FF2351ADFCB0FC3B" blockId="19.[151,1437,1386,2025]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis id="B976EACBFFDDE356FF2351ADFDFBFC1F" bold="true" box="[199,539,1782,1809]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Natural history and habitat.</emphasis>
The specimens from Tandil were collected with pitfall traps, placed on sites in rocky hillsides (
<quantity id="4CFA9B3CFFDDE356FEAE5040FE2EFC3A" box="[330,462,1818,1845]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.915" metricValueMax="4.6" metricValueMin="3.2299999999999995" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="m" value="391.5" valueMax="460.0" valueMin="323.0">323–460 m</quantity>
), with grasses of different heights.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3186552FFDDE356FF235064FD5EFCE6" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BBD36D9FFDDE356FF235064FB1DFC56" blockId="19.[151,1437,1386,2025]" box="[199,1277,1854,1881]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
